  <data name="FullDescription" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>An external entity that initiates a data flow into the system should authenticate itself so the elements it calls can verify who is acting. When it does not authenticate itself (AuthenticatesItself = No or unset), an attacker can spoof its identity and act on its behalf.

This rule is violated for any external interactor whose AuthenticatesItself property is not Yes and that has an outbound data flow to a non-external element.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="HelpText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Require the external entity to present a verifiable identity (for example a client certificate, a signed token, or an API key bound to the caller), validate it on the receiving element, and set the external entity's AuthenticatesItself property to Yes.

If the entity does not actually initiate flows into the system, correct the direction of the data flow so the diagram reflects reality.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="MessageText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>External entity [{0}] initiates data flows into the system but does not authenticate itself, allowing an attacker to spoof its identity.</value>
